---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const symptoms = [
  { id: 'hot-flashes',  num: '01', name: 'Hot Flashes',    color: '#B84A2E', img: 'photo-1571019613454-1cb2f99b2d8b' },
  { id: 'brain-fog',    num: '02', name: 'Brain Fog',       color: '#2D5F7A', img: 'photo-1580130732478-4e339fb33746' },
  { id: 'mood-swings',  num: '03', name: 'Mood Swings',     color: '#3D7A5F', img: 'photo-1499209974431-9dddcece7f88' },
  { id: 'sleep',        num: '04', name: 'Sleep Problems',  color: '#1A2D4A', img: 'photo-1455642305367-68834a1da7ab' },
  { id: 'weight',       num: '05', name: 'Weight Changes',  color: '#8A5230', img: 'photo-1434682966571-95c657f41aa6' },
  { id: 'hair-loss',    num: '06', name: 'Hair Loss',       color: '#5A6B4E', img: 'photo-1522337660859-02fbefca4702' },
];
---
<Layout
  title="Know Your Symptoms — The Second Spring"
  description="What's actually happening when you have hot flashes, brain fog, mood swings, sleep problems, weight changes, and hair loss — and what genuinely helps."
>

<main class="sc-page">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div class="sc-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="sc-eyebrow">Symptom Guide</p>
      <h1 class="sc-title">Know What's Happening</h1>
      <p class="sc-subtitle">Every symptom has a biological reason. Understanding it is the first step to managing it.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Sticky nav -->
  <nav class="sc-nav" aria-label="Jump to symptom">
    <div class="sc-nav-inner">
      {symptoms.map(s => (
        <a href={`#${s.id}`} class="sc-nav-pill" style={`--pill-color:${s.color}`}>{s.name}</a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- ── 01 HOT FLASHES ── -->
  <section class="sc-card" id="hot-flashes">
    <div class="sc-card-photo">
      <img
        src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1571019613454-1cb2f99b2d8b?w=1000&q=80&fit=crop"
        alt="Woman experiencing perimenopause hot flashes"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <div class="sc-photo-overlay" style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(184,74,46,0.3) 0%, rgba(184,74,46,0.85) 100%);">
        <span class="sc-num">01</span>
        <div class="sc-photo-title">
          <h2 class="sc-name">Hot Flashes</h2>
          <p class="sc-hook">"Your hypothalamus has lost its thermostat. Here's how to work with it."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="sc-card-body">
      <div class="sc-grid">
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head">Why this happens</div>
          <p>Oestrogen normally keeps your hypothalamus's temperature regulator in a very narrow range. When it fluctuates, that thermostat becomes hypersensitive — a warm room, a sip of wine, a moment of stress registers as overheating. The result: sudden blood vessel dilation, a rush of heat, sweating, followed by a chill. It is a real physiological event, not anxiety.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-warn">What makes it worse</div>
          <ul class="sc-list">
            <li>Alcohol — even one drink</li>
            <li>Spicy food and hot drinks</li>
            <li>Synthetic, tight clothing</li>
            <li>Stress and sudden temperature change</li>
            <li>Smoking</li>
            <li>Caffeine in large amounts</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-help">What actually helps</div>
          <ul class="sc-list sc-list-green">
            <li>Dress in breathable layers you can remove</li>
            <li>Keep the bedroom at 18–20°C</li>
            <li>Paced breathing during an episode (4 counts in, 4 out)</li>
            <li>Reduce alcohol and caffeine</li>
            <li>Strength training reduces frequency over time</li>
            <li>HRT — the most effective treatment; discuss with your gynaecologist</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block sc-block-myth">
          <div class="sc-block-head">The myth</div>
          <p class="sc-myth-text">"Hot flashes are just feeling a bit warm."</p>
          <p>They are not. Skin temperature measurably rises, heart rate increases, blood vessels dilate. They are genuine physiological events — not imagined, not emotional, not a sign you cannot cope. Some women have 10 or more episodes a day. That is a medical situation, not a mood.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sc-doctor-bar" style="border-left:3px solid #B84A2E;">
        <span class="sc-doctor-label">See a doctor if</span>
        <span>More than 7 episodes per day, lasting more than 10 minutes each, or significantly disrupting sleep for weeks on end.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── 02 BRAIN FOG ── -->
  <section class="sc-card" id="brain-fog">
    <div class="sc-card-photo">
      <img
        src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1580130732478-4e339fb33746?w=1000&q=80&fit=crop"
        alt="Woman with brain fog and difficulty concentrating"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <div class="sc-photo-overlay" style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(45,95,122,0.3) 0%, rgba(45,95,122,0.88) 100%);">
        <span class="sc-num">02</span>
        <div class="sc-photo-title">
          <h2 class="sc-name">Brain Fog</h2>
          <p class="sc-hook">"The word is still in there. Oestrogen was helping you find it."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="sc-card-body">
      <div class="sc-grid">
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head">Why this happens</div>
          <p>Oestrogen supports acetylcholine — the neurotransmitter most involved in memory, attention, and processing speed. It also increases blood flow to areas of the brain used for verbal memory. When oestrogen fluctuates in perimenopause, cognitive performance measurably changes: word retrieval slows, focus scatters, multitasking becomes harder. This is not dementia. It is temporary hormonal disruption of brain chemistry.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-warn">What makes it worse</div>
          <ul class="sc-list">
            <li>Poor sleep — the single biggest driver</li>
            <li>High sustained stress</li>
            <li>Alcohol</li>
            <li>Sedentary lifestyle</li>
            <li>Dehydration</li>
            <li>Low vitamin B12 or vitamin D</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-help">What actually helps</div>
          <ul class="sc-list sc-list-green">
            <li>Sleep — nothing else works well without it</li>
            <li>Daily aerobic exercise (brisk walking improves brain blood flow)</li>
            <li>Write things down — managing a temporary deficit, not permanent loss</li>
            <li>Reduce multitasking; give your brain one task</li>
            <li>Check B12, vitamin D, and iron</li>
            <li>HRT — many women report significant cognitive improvement</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block sc-block-myth">
          <div class="sc-block-head">The myth</div>
          <p class="sc-myth-text">"This is the beginning of dementia."</p>
          <p>It is not. Perimenopause brain fog is non-progressive, driven by hormonal fluctuation rather than neurodegeneration, and typically improves after menopause when the hormonal environment stabilises. Dementia does not come and go with your menstrual cycle. If your fog is worse before periods and better after — it is hormonal.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sc-doctor-bar" style="border-left:3px solid #2D5F7A;">
        <span class="sc-doctor-label">See a doctor if</span>
        <span>Forgetting people you know well, getting lost in familiar places, or noticing progressive deterioration over months — these warrant evaluation to rule out other causes.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── 03 MOOD SWINGS ── -->
  <section class="sc-card" id="mood-swings">
    <div class="sc-card-photo">
      <img
        src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1499209974431-9dddcece7f88?w=1000&q=80&fit=crop"
        alt="Woman dealing with mood swings and emotional changes"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <div class="sc-photo-overlay" style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(61,122,95,0.3) 0%, rgba(61,122,95,0.88) 100%);">
        <span class="sc-num">03</span>
        <div class="sc-photo-title">
          <h2 class="sc-name">Mood Swings</h2>
          <p class="sc-hook">"You haven't changed. Your oestrogen has."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="sc-card-body">
      <div class="sc-grid">
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head">Why this happens</div>
          <p>Oestrogen and progesterone both regulate serotonin and GABA — the brain chemicals responsible for mood stability and emotional buffering. When these hormones swing erratically in perimenopause, the nervous system loses its ability to absorb small frustrations. Triggers that you'd once have handled without a thought produce outsized reactions. The shame that follows — "why did I react like that?" — is one of the least-discussed parts of perimenopause.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-warn">What makes it worse</div>
          <ul class="sc-list">
            <li>Poor sleep — amplifies every emotional reaction</li>
            <li>High stress and no recovery time</li>
            <li>Alcohol (disrupts serotonin)</li>
            <li>Isolation — carrying it alone</li>
            <li>The week before a period when oestrogen drops sharply</li>
            <li>Skipping meals (blood sugar drops lower the threshold)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-help">What actually helps</div>
          <ul class="sc-list sc-list-green">
            <li>Regular sleep schedule — the foundation for everything</li>
            <li>Daily movement, even a 20-minute walk</li>
            <li>Tell your family what's happening — context reduces conflict</li>
            <li>Progesterone (prescribed) helps especially in second half of cycle</li>
            <li>Therapy or CBT — strong evidence for perimenopause mood</li>
            <li>HRT stabilises the hormonal swings that drive the reactions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block sc-block-myth">
          <div class="sc-block-head">The myth</div>
          <p class="sc-myth-text">"This is who you are becoming."</p>
          <p>It is not. The vast majority of women describe returning to emotional baseline once hormones stabilise — with HRT or after post-menopause settles. The irritability, the low threshold, the disproportionate reactions — these are symptoms of a hormonal state, not a character change. You are not becoming a different person. Your brain chemistry is temporarily disrupted.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sc-doctor-bar" style="border-left:3px solid #3D7A5F;">
        <span class="sc-doctor-label">See a doctor if</span>
        <span>Depression lasting more than two weeks, thoughts of self-harm (call iCall: 9152987821, emergency: 112), or anxiety that is preventing you from functioning at work or at home.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── 04 SLEEP ── -->
  <section class="sc-card" id="sleep">
    <div class="sc-card-photo">
      <img
        src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1455642305367-68834a1da7ab?w=1000&q=80&fit=crop"
        alt="Woman struggling with sleep problems at night"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <div class="sc-photo-overlay" style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(26,45,74,0.3) 0%, rgba(26,45,74,0.92) 100%);">
        <span class="sc-num">04</span>
        <div class="sc-photo-title">
          <h2 class="sc-name">Sleep Problems</h2>
          <p class="sc-hook">"3am is hormonal, not existential. Usually."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="sc-card-body">
      <div class="sc-grid">
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head">Why this happens</div>
          <p>Oestrogen regulates the sleep-wake cycle and body temperature. Night sweats wake you up repeatedly. Progesterone — which has natural sleep-promoting, calming effects — declines first in perimenopause. Cortisol patterns shift, producing early waking at 3–4am with a racing mind. The result is not one problem but three: difficulty falling asleep, staying asleep, and waking too early — often all happening together.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-warn">What makes it worse</div>
          <ul class="sc-list">
            <li>Alcohol — disrupts REM even though it feels sedating</li>
            <li>Caffeine after 2pm</li>
            <li>Warm bedroom (above 20°C)</li>
            <li>Irregular wake times (varies more than 1 hour)</li>
            <li>Screens close to bed</li>
            <li>Sleeping tablets for more than 2–3 weeks</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-help">What actually helps</div>
          <ul class="sc-list sc-list-green">
            <li>Consistent wake time — the single most powerful sleep lever</li>
            <li>Bedroom at 18–20°C, blackout, phone out of the room</li>
            <li>No alcohol — even one drink fragments sleep in perimenopause</li>
            <li>Micronised progesterone (prescribed) has strong evidence for sleep improvement</li>
            <li>HRT addresses the night sweats that are waking you up</li>
            <li>CBT-I — best long-term evidence for insomnia; better than tablets</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block sc-block-myth">
          <div class="sc-block-head">The myth</div>
          <p class="sc-myth-text">"I just need a sleeping tablet."</p>
          <p>Sleeping tablets treat the symptom, not the cause. They lose effectiveness within 2–4 weeks as the body builds tolerance. The root cause — hormonal disruption of the sleep system — remains untouched. CBT-I (Cognitive Behavioural Therapy for Insomnia) has better long-term outcomes than medication. And for many women, addressing the perimenopause itself with HRT resolves the sleep problem at its source.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sc-doctor-bar" style="border-left:3px solid #1A2D4A;">
        <span class="sc-doctor-label">See a doctor if</span>
        <span>Sleeping less than 5 hours regularly, new loud snoring (sleep apnoea risk increases in perimenopause), or daytime function is significantly impaired by fatigue.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── 05 WEIGHT ── -->
  <section class="sc-card" id="weight">
    <div class="sc-card-photo">
      <img
        src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1434682966571-95c657f41aa6?w=1000&q=80&fit=crop"
        alt="Healthy food and body weight management during perimenopause"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <div class="sc-photo-overlay" style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(138,82,48,0.3) 0%, rgba(138,82,48,0.88) 100%);">
        <span class="sc-num">05</span>
        <div class="sc-photo-title">
          <h2 class="sc-name">Weight Changes</h2>
          <p class="sc-hook">"Your body didn't stop listening. It started storing differently."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="sc-card-body">
      <div class="sc-grid">
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head">Why this happens</div>
          <p>Oestrogen regulates where fat is stored. As it falls, the body shifts storage from hips and thighs to the abdomen — specifically deep visceral fat around the organs. Simultaneously, muscle mass begins declining (sarcopenia), lowering the resting metabolic rate. Insulin sensitivity worsens. You can eat exactly what you always ate and gain weight, because your body is using and storing it differently.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-warn">What makes it worse</div>
          <ul class="sc-list">
            <li>Refined carbohydrates and added sugar</li>
            <li>Sedentary lifestyle — especially no strength training</li>
            <li>Poor sleep (raises cortisol, drives abdominal fat)</li>
            <li>Chronic stress</li>
            <li>Severe calorie restriction — accelerates muscle loss</li>
            <li>Alcohol — calorie-dense and disrupts fat metabolism</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-help">What actually helps</div>
          <ul class="sc-list sc-list-green">
            <li>Strength training — the most important intervention; builds metabolic muscle</li>
            <li>Adequate protein (1.2–1.6g per kg body weight per day)</li>
            <li>Reduce refined carbs and sugar — not total calories</li>
            <li>Fix sleep — cortisol from poor sleep drives abdominal fat directly</li>
            <li>Manage stress — cortisol is a fat-storage hormone</li>
            <li>Think body composition, not scale weight</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block sc-block-myth">
          <div class="sc-block-head">The myth</div>
          <p class="sc-myth-text">"Eating less will fix it."</p>
          <p>Severe calorie restriction in perimenopause typically backfires. It accelerates muscle loss, worsens fatigue, raises cortisol (which drives abdominal fat storage), and rarely produces sustained fat loss. The body defends its fat stores more aggressively when muscle is also being lost. The solution is changing body composition — more muscle, less visceral fat — which requires strength training, not starvation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sc-doctor-bar" style="border-left:3px solid #8A5230;">
        <span class="sc-doctor-label">See a doctor if</span>
        <span>Rapid unexplained weight gain of more than 4–5 kg over a few months, significant abdominal swelling, or weight gain accompanied by fatigue and cold intolerance — check thyroid.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── 06 HAIR LOSS ── -->
  <section class="sc-card" id="hair-loss">
    <div class="sc-card-photo">
      <img
        src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1522337660859-02fbefca4702?w=1000&q=80&fit=crop"
        alt="Woman concerned about hair loss during perimenopause"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <div class="sc-photo-overlay" style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(90,107,78,0.3) 0%, rgba(90,107,78,0.9) 100%);">
        <span class="sc-num">06</span>
        <div class="sc-photo-title">
          <h2 class="sc-name">Hair Loss</h2>
          <p class="sc-hook">"It's not all coming out. It just feels that way."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="sc-card-body">
      <div class="sc-grid">
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head">Why this happens</div>
          <p>Oestrogen prolongs the active growth phase of the hair cycle. When it falls, more hairs shift into the shedding phase simultaneously — which is why the volume of hair in the shower drain feels alarming. Androgens also become relatively more dominant as oestrogen falls, miniaturising hair follicles at the crown and temples. This is the same mechanism as male pattern hair loss, but in women it typically produces diffuse thinning rather than complete baldness.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-warn">What makes it worse</div>
          <ul class="sc-list">
            <li>Low ferritin — even when haemoglobin is normal</li>
            <li>Vitamin D deficiency</li>
            <li>Thyroid disease (very common in this age group)</li>
            <li>High sustained stress (telogen effluvium)</li>
            <li>Crash dieting and inadequate protein</li>
            <li>Tight hairstyles, heat styling</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block">
          <div class="sc-block-head sc-head-help">What actually helps</div>
          <ul class="sc-list sc-list-green">
            <li>Get bloodwork first: ferritin (needs to be above 50, not just "in range"), thyroid, vitamin D, zinc</li>
            <li>Correct any deficiencies — ferritin correction alone can significantly reduce shedding</li>
            <li>Adequate dietary protein daily</li>
            <li>Topical hair treatments — ask a dermatologist which is appropriate</li>
            <li>HRT restores oestrogen's protective effect on follicles</li>
            <li>Patience: hair responds in 4–6 months minimum</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sc-block sc-block-myth">
          <div class="sc-block-head">The myth</div>
          <p class="sc-myth-text">"The hair is gone permanently."</p>
          <p>In most cases of hormonally-driven perimenopause hair thinning, the follicle is still alive — it has miniaturised, not died. With the right nutritional support and targeted treatment, recovery is possible. What does not work: expensive shampoos, biotin supplements in isolation, or waiting for it to resolve on its own. What does work: fixing the underlying cause (nutritional deficiency, hormonal, thyroid) and adding targeted treatment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sc-doctor-bar" style="border-left:3px solid #5A6B4E;">
        <span class="sc-doctor-label">See a doctor if</span>
        <span>Patchy bald spots rather than diffuse thinning (warrants evaluation for alopecia areata), very rapid loss over weeks, or hair loss alongside significant fatigue and weight changes.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Footer CTA -->
  <div class="sc-footer-cta">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Still have questions?</h2>
      <p>Our companion is available any time — ask about your specific symptoms, what tests to request, or what to say to your doctor.</p>
      <a href="/chat" class="sc-cta-btn">Talk to Our Companion</a>
    </div>
  </div>

</main>

</Layout>

<style>
  /* ── Page ── */
  .sc-page { background: #F2F5F3; }
  .container { max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 1.25rem; }

  /* ── Hero ── */
  .sc-hero {
    background: linear-gradient(150deg, #0F2A1A 0%, #1A3D2B 100%);
    padding: 5rem 1.25rem 4rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .sc-eyebrow {
    font-size: .72rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: .14em; color: #8BAF98; margin-bottom: .75rem;
  }
  .sc-title {
    font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 5vw, 3.2rem); font-weight: 900;
    color: #fff; line-height: 1.1; margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .sc-subtitle {
    font-size: 1.05rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,.7);
    max-width: 540px; margin: 0 auto; line-height: 1.75;
  }

  /* ── Nav ── */
  .sc-nav {
    background: #fff; border-bottom: 1.5px solid #DDE8E3;
    position: sticky; top: 0; z-index: 100;
    box-shadow: 0 2px 16px rgba(0,0,0,.07);
  }
  .sc-nav-inner {
    max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto; padding: .8rem 1.25rem;
    display: flex; gap: .5rem; overflow-x: auto; scrollbar-width: none;
  }
  .sc-nav-inner::-webkit-scrollbar { display: none; }
  .sc-nav-pill {
    padding: .42rem 1.05rem; border-radius: 99px; font-size: .82rem;
    font-weight: 600; color: var(--pill-color, #3D7A5F);
    background: #F0F5F2; border: 1.5px solid transparent;
    white-space: nowrap; text-decoration: none; transition: all .18s; flex-shrink: 0;
  }
  .sc-nav-pill:hover {
    background: var(--pill-color, #3D7A5F); color: #fff;
  }

  /* ── Cards ── */
  .sc-card {
    margin: 2.5rem auto; max-width: 1000px; border-radius: 20px;
    overflow: hidden; box-shadow: 0 6px 32px rgba(0,0,0,.10); background: #fff;
  }

  /* Photo section */
  .sc-card-photo { position: relative; height: 320px; overflow: hidden; }
  .sc-card-photo img {
    width: 100%; height: 100%; object-fit: cover; object-position: center top;
    display: block;
  }
  .sc-photo-overlay {
    position: absolute; inset: 0;
    display: flex; align-items: flex-end; gap: 1.25rem;
    padding: 1.75rem 2rem;
  }
  .sc-num {
    font-size: 3.5rem; font-weight: 900; color: rgba(255,255,255,.25);
    line-height: 1; flex-shrink: 0; align-self: flex-end; padding-bottom: .1rem;
    font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums;
  }
  .sc-photo-title { flex: 1; }
  .sc-name {
    font-size: clamp(1.7rem, 4vw, 2.4rem); font-weight: 900;
    color: #fff; margin-bottom: .4rem; line-height: 1.1;
    text-shadow: 0 1px 4px rgba(0,0,0,.3);
  }
  .sc-hook {
    font-size: 1rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,.88); font-style: italic;
    line-height: 1.55; text-shadow: 0 1px 3px rgba(0,0,0,.3); margin: 0;
  }

  /* Body */
  .sc-card-body { padding: 2rem 2.5rem 1.75rem; }

  /* Grid 2×2 */
  .sc-grid {
    display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
